  "prompt": "Why do many Indian Christians keep Hindu names?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why many Indian Christians retain Hindu names:\n\n1. Cultural Identity\n- Names are an important part of cultural heritage\n- Keeping traditional names helps maintain connection to family and cultural roots\n\n2. Family Traditions\n- Many families prefer to maintain their ancestral naming practices\n- Parents may want to honor family history and traditions\n\n3. Linguistic Comfort\n- Hindu names are often linguistically familiar and easier to pronounce\n- They sound natural in the local language context\n\n4. Social Integration\n- Using traditional names helps avoid potential social discrimination\n- Prevents being immediately identified as a religious minority\n\n5. Personal Choice\n- Many Christians see no conflict between their religious beliefs and traditional names\n- Names are viewed as cultural, not necessarily religious, markers\n\n6. Biblical Precedent\n- Some biblical figures had names from surrounding cultures\n- Christianity does not mandate changing one's name upon conversion\n\n7. Historical Conversion Practices\n- Early Christian missionaries often did not insist on name changes\n- Conversions were generally more focused on spiritual transformation\n\nThese reasons reflect the complex cultural dynamics of religious identity in India, where religious and cultural boundaries are often fluid and nuanced.",
